Introduction ¶

Phase 1 Summary¶

In the Phase 1 report, our goal was to identify which categorical variables in the dataset that had the most impact on our predictive model. In this case, it was to determine the life expectancies of people around the world based on their environmental factors such as their country's obesity rate, regions they live in, bmi levels etc. In order to visualise this, we first had to preprocess our data and cleanse it to remove any variables that were irrelevant to the model. This consisted of dropping variables of NaN type which was the most practical approach. However it was discovered that after imputing all rows that contained NaN values, we ended up with 2 rows in total with the dataset. This resulted in an impractical dataset, so therefore after analysing the original dataset, we came to a conclusion to remove columns we assumed were irrelevant. This was based on counting how many NaN values those columns contained, so logically columns with NaN values more than 3 digits were dropped as they contained little to no data. In this way, we decided to rely more on logic rather than speculation, optimising columns we deemed 'unecessary' to provide a more accurate dataset to work with.

After the data preprocessing stage, the next part of the first phase was to visualise and explore the data to grasp a further understanding of our main objective. This consisted of plotting different types of graphs and analysing them to provide explanations of correlations between variables. In doing so, some of our speculations and predictions proved to be incorrect based off the data provided in the plots. Hence, this is why visualisation is important as we assumed that there would be a linear correlation between high bmi and low life expectancy but that was proven false based on some of the scatter plots provided in the three-variable plots.

Report Overview¶

In this report, we will be producing a statistical model. This consists of a full model by fitting a multiple linear regression for the variable life_expect using our cleansed dataset produced in the first phase. After doing so, we must perform a full model diagnostic check to make sure our model is consistent and does not impede any regression assumptions. When this stage has been completed, we need to run a backwards feature selection using p-values to determine which features are irrelevant to our dependent variable in predicting our life expectancies.

Overview of Methodology¶

The methodology will consist of a full model. As we do not have many independent variables, we will be manually adding all the independent variables to our construct our regression formula. In this way, we are able to use the Statsmodels module to produce a statistical model formula. As a result of this, we are able to encode our data into an OLS model. After doing so, we will use the R-squared value to determine the variance and the p-values to determine which variables are significant for our predictive model.

Full Model Diagnostic Checks¶

The main purpose of this is to check whether there are violations of the regression assumptions which are listed below:

  1. linearity of the relationship between target feature and independent features
  2. constant variance of the residuals (Homoscedasticity, avoid heteroscedasticity)
  3. residuals are normally distributed
  4. statistical independence of the residuals

Although questionable, from figure 12, we can see that this histogram is particularly right-skewed. However, it is also arguable that this histogram can also be somewhat symmetrical. As a result of this, we are able to assume that the data provided is a normal distrbution.

The reason as of to why the residuals are ranged at -1 to 1 is due to the fact that the dataset provided was extremely accurate. This is not a common case as usually there would be more normality to different cases and the scatterplots would be more clearer. The scatterplots are actually random but there are just so many clusters of variables that they clump up making it hard to decypher.

Backwards Feature Selection¶

The next stage of this diagnostic check is to perform some sort of backward feature selection by utilising the p-values. As Statsmodels does not contain this feature, we have borrowed the code of 'David Akman', RMIT Professor of Mathematics of Computing 2 (MATH2412).

In [180]:
## create the patsy model description from formula
patsy_description = patsy.ModelDesc.from_formula(formula_str_encoded)

# initialize feature-selected fit to full model
linreg_fit = full_model.fit()

# do backwards elimination using p-values
p_val_cutoff = 0.05

## WARNING 1: The code below assumes that the Intercept term is present in the model.
## WARNING 2: It will work only with main effects and two-way interactions, if any.

print('\nPerforming backwards feature selection using p-values:')

while True:

    # uncomment the line below if you would like to see the regression summary
    # in each step:
    ### print(linreg_fit.summary())

    pval_series = linreg_fit.pvalues.drop(labels='Intercept')
    pval_series = pval_series.sort_values(ascending=False)
    term = pval_series.index[0]
    pval = pval_series[0]
    if (pval < p_val_cutoff):
        break
    term_components = term.split(':')
    print(f'\nRemoving term "{term}" with p-value {pval:.4}')
    if (len(term_components) == 1): ## this is a main effect term
        patsy_description.rhs_termlist.remove(patsy.Term([patsy.EvalFactor(term_components[0])]))    
    else: ## this is an interaction term
        patsy_description.rhs_termlist.remove(patsy.Term([patsy.EvalFactor(term_components[0]), 
                                                        patsy.EvalFactor(term_components[1])]))    

    linreg_fit = smf.ols(formula=patsy_description, data=df_encoded).fit()

###
## this is the clean fit after backwards elimination
model_reduced_fitted = smf.ols(formula = patsy_description, data = df_encoded).fit()
###

print("\n***")
print(model_reduced_fitted.summary())
print("***")
print(f"Regression number of terms: {len(model_reduced_fitted.model.exog_names)}")

plt.title('Figure 7: Scatter plot of residuals vs. predicted Life Expectancy for Reduced Model', fontsize=15)
plt.show();

As predicted, Figure 7 is identical on an eye level to the graph in Figure 2. The patterns are the same with points being consistent on top and below the zero line.

Judging form this outcome, we are going to predict that the histogram is also going to be the same, as it is a logical assumption due to the fact that the dataframe of this new model is exactly the same as the full model.

Critique & Limitations ¶

With the cleaned dataset retrieved from Phase 1, it was quite unexpected that after some statistical modelling we found out that there was an enormous correlation between the dependent variable 'Life Expectancy' and all the other independent variables. This meant that whatever statistical modelling method we apply, we would get an almost one to one correlation between the dependent variable and all the independent variables. As a result of this we are able to conclude that the construction of the categorical variables in the dataset were extremely logical. In this sense, we can be certain that by using this statistical model with these exact categorical variables, we are able to accurately predict the life expectancy of a person in a given country or region with certain bmis etc. with a 99% variance.

However, since the model was so accurate, we were not able to really interpret most of the graphs. Take Figure 5 and 8 for example, they were histograms with x values ranging from -1 to 1 with only 3 'bars' visible. In this case it was quite hard to determine if it was actually normally distributed data or not. Furthermore, this also applied to Figures 2, 3 and 7. From observing those scatterplots, it was quite impossible to determine whether or not those points on the graph were scattered randomly or not due to many clusters of values. This clouded the our interpretation of the graph as we ideally want a graph that is scattered randomly.

Summary & Conclusions ¶

Project Summary¶

In the phase 1 of the project, we needed to preprocess the data in order for it to be 'clean' for our statistical modelling in this phase of the project. We approached this by cleansing the data by removing columns that contained more than 3 digit NaN values. After this we dropped all new rows which contained NaN values resulting in a clean dataset. We then performed some data exploration and visualisation by plotting these rows and columns into graphs such as histograms, scatterplots and barplots to find some sort of correlation between the different types of variables.

In Phase 2 of the project, we used the clean data to create a statistical model to predict whether or not an average person's life expectancy was based on the numerous categorical variables provided. In order to determine this, we produced a full and reduced model by using the independent variables as the statistical model's formula. We needed to perform an automatic variable selection in order to plug the String equation into the Statsmodels module. This was performed by a one-hot-encoding process using the get_dummies() function in tne pandas module. After that we were able to obtain an OLS table where we could determine the R-squared and the p-values. We used the R-squared value to create new dataframe plots. The p-values were used as well for the next stage of backwards feature selection to create the reduced model. After this we performed the diagnostic tests to see whether or not these values complied with the rules.

Summary of Findings¶

The initial goal of this project was to predict the life expectancy of people based on different factors surrounding them. Phase 1 has contributed to a simple analysis of this goal as we explored many types of plots to determine whether or not there was a correlation between the categorical and numerical variables. It was concluded in the first phase that there would be different correlations as some variables are independent from other variables. Such was depicted in the BMI vs Life expectancy as we had speculated that there was NO correlation between them. We wanted to prove this by introducing statistical modelling in Phase 2.

Phase 2 provided us with more definite answers and foresight via technical analysis of the regression model. The full model given us an R-squared value of 0.9994. This was extremely unexpected as we had conlcuded that there were variables which had nob correlation. No definitive solution was provided as to why this was the case, but we can merely speculate that the original dataset provided was extremely accurate. This might have been the case as extensive research had probably gone into the construction of this dataset due to it being on the World Health Organisation website.

Conclusion¶

It was concluded that this project had proved that it was possible to determine someones life expectancy based on their environmental factors. This model was made for the average human hence why the R-squared value was close to 1. However there may be more factors that could alter our statistics as more categorical data could be introduced in the dataset related to variables. This project was an eye opener as of to why statistics is important as we cannot merely make speculations based on simple analysis of data. This was proven as we had previously hypothesised that factors such as BMI and Life expectancy had no correlation, however the statistics had proven us wrong otherwise. In hindsight, the project was a success on the grounds that we were able to determine the life expectancies of average people based on their environmental factors.
